I invoke this script from another script that runs it hundreds of times.  One time in 500 or so it segfaults.  The output when it segfaults is:

load user(1):
barf:
load user(2):

So it seems it segfaults when it goes to perform a query on a collection *after* the query has timed out and the exception is thrown.  The users collection for what it's worth is indexed on sid and uid, both ascending.  sids are stored as integers; uids that fit in 32 bits (such as the one in the example) are stored as ints.  There are other uids that are stored as floats (larger values) and strings (there are some alphanumeric uids).

