According to the documentation, Mongo::connect() is supposed to either return a boolean true on success, or an exception on failure.  But on version 1.0.10 of the driver, it is really doing is this:

     php > $x = new Mongo('mongodb://mongo.my.com:27017');
     php > $y = $x->connect();
     php > var_export($y);
     NULL

The funny thing is, I can actually use $x to fiddle with my database, so the connect() command succeeded.  It is easy to work around, of course, but this bug broke code that has been working reliably for months.

Now here's the same commands, issued against version 1.0.9 of the PHP driver:

     php > $x = new Mongo('mongodb://mongo.my.com:27017');
     php > $y = $x->connect();
     php > var_export($y);
     true

So, version 1.0.9 does what the docs claim.

