Documents in the system.profile collection do not have _id fields, contrary to the statement from http://www.mongodb.org/display/DOCS/Object+IDs that "Documents in MongoDB are required to have a key, _id, which uniquely identifies them." 

Q1. Is this a bug (that _id fields are missing)?
Q2. Are there any other collections that may not have _id fields?
Q3. Assuming this is intentional and not a bug, could you update the page linked above to note that system.profile is an exception?

The issue I ran into today is that the PHP driver returns the same empty string key for every document in the system.profile collection, which in turn led unexpected behavior using iterator_to_array.

The same issue occurs if the _ids are not numbers or strings. For example, using iterator_to_array on a collection with the documents given below would result in an associative array with a single element whose key is "Array":
> db.foo.insert({_id:{foo:1}});
> db.foo.insert({_id:{foo:2}});

Q4. Could you add a note about these edge cases (missing and casted _ids) in the recommendation to use iterator_to_array in the PHP manual? A suggestion to pass the second parameter as false (i.e. iterator_to_array($cursor, false)) should be sufficient. http://php.net/manual/en/mongocollection.find.php

Steps To Reproduce:
Run the following test case.

<?php
/*

Example output:

cursor1 retrieved 1 item(s) from system.profile
cursor2 retrieved 3 item(s) from system.profile
cursor3 retrieved 3 item(s) from system.profile

*/

$connectionURI = 'mongodb://localhost/';
$collection = 'system.profile';

$mongo = new Mongo($connectionURI);
$adminDB = $mongo->selectDB('admin');

// Make sure there is some minimum amount of data to be selected
generateProfilingData($adminDB);

// This method will not always work
$cursor1 = $adminDB->selectCollection($collection)->find()->limit(100);
$data1 = iterator_to_array($cursor1);

// This method should work every time
$cursor2 = $adminDB->selectCollection($collection)->find()->limit(100);
$data2 = iterator_to_array($cursor2, false);

// This method should work every time
$cursor3 = $adminDB->selectCollection($collection)->find()->limit(100);
$data3 = array();
foreach($cursor2 as $data) {
	$data3[] = $data;
}

echo 'cursor1 retrieved ',count($data1)," item(s) from $collection\n";
echo 'cursor2 retrieved ',count($data2)," item(s) from $collection\n";
echo 'cursor3 retrieved ',count($data3)," item(s) from $collection\n";


function generateProfilingData($db) {
	$db->setProfilingLevel(2);

	$cursor = $db->selectCollection('system.indexes')->find();
	iterator_to_array($cursor);
	$cursor = $db->selectCollection('system.indexes')->find();
	iterator_to_array($cursor);

	$db->setProfilingLevel(0);
}

