The PHP driver allows the creation of collections named "" (empty string). Collections with empty names cause conflicts with some aspect of database dumps or replication sets (I believe an empty-named collection is created as part of one of those processes).

I'm filing this bug because I heard the following (paraphrased):
bq. I think the MongoDB creates the "" database as part of the dump or restore process... I can't remember exactly when.  The PHP driver doesn't let you create or use "" as a database, so file the bug with the Core Server project.
However, since the PHP driver does indeed allow you to create and use such a collection, it seems like a driver bug.

STEPS TO REPRODUCE

1. Run the following script
{code:php}
<?php
// Mongo PHP driver 1.1.0

try {
	$mongo = new Mongo('mongodb://localhost');
	$db = $mongo->test;

	$collection = $db->createCollection('');
	// $collection = $db->createCollection('', true, 500000, 1000);
	echo 'Just created a collection named "'.$collection->getName()."\"\n";

	$collection->insert(array('test'=>'foo'));

}catch(MongoException $e) {
	var_dump($e);
}
?>
{code}

2. Confirm the collection was created in the Mongo shell:
> use test;
> db.getCollectionNames();
[ "", "system.indexes" ]
> db[""].find();
{ "_id" : ObjectId("4d..."), "test" : "foo" }

